Section 9 of the Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996, deals with interim measures by a court. It states that a party may, before or during arbitral proceedings or at any time after the making of the arbitral award but before it is enforced, apply to a court for an interim measure of protection. 

The court may grant the following interim measures:
- to preserve the subject-matter of the dispute;
- to take interim custody of the subject-matter of the dispute or to appoint a person to take such custody;
- to appoint a receiver to manage the subject-matter of the dispute;
- to take other interim measures for the purpose of preserving evidence or to prevent the dissipation of assets that could be the subject of the arbitral award.

(Section 9, Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996)

IPC 141 refers to the Indian Penal Code, 1860. Section 141 of the IPC defines "unlawful assembly" as an assembly of five or more persons with the intention to commit an offense or to cause disturbance to the public peace by using criminal force or show of criminal force.

According to Section 141 of the IPC:
"Unlawful assembly.- An assembly of five or more persons is designated an 'unlawful assembly' if the common object of the persons composing that assembly is-

First.- To overawe by criminal force, or show of criminal force, the Central or any State Government or Parliament or the Legislature of any State, or any public servant in the exercise of the public functions;
or
Second.- To resist the execution of any law or of any legal process;
or
Third.- To commit any mischief or criminal trespass, or other offense;
or
Fourth.- By means of criminal force, or show of criminal force, to any person to take or obtain possession of any property, or to deprive him of the enjoyment of a right of way, or of the use of water or other incorporeal right;
or
Fifth.- By means of criminal force, or show of criminal force, to compel any person to do what he is not legally bound to do, or to omit to do what he is legally entitled to do."

